# TypeScript / Node.js Standards

## Principles

- DRY: extract repeated logic into shared utils or services
- KISS: prefer simple, readable code over clever abstractions
- YAGNI: don't build what isn't needed yet
- Fail fast: validate inputs early, throw meaningful errors
- Single responsibility: one function/module = one job

## TypeScript

- Strict mode always (`"strict": true`)
- No `any` — use `unknown` and narrow with type guards
- Prefer `interface` for public APIs, `type` for unions/composition
- Explicit return types on all exported functions
- Use `as const` for literal objects/arrays that shouldn't widen

## Architecture

Feature-based folder structure:

```
src/
  features/
    orders/
      orders.service.ts
      orders.controller.ts
      orders.schema.ts
      orders.test.ts
  shared/
    utils/
    middleware/
    errors/
  config/
  db.ts
  index.ts
```

- Keep business logic out of route handlers
- Services handle logic, controllers handle HTTP
- Controllers parse request → call service → send response
- Use dependency injection over direct imports for testability

## Error Handling

Custom error classes with status codes:

```typescript
export class AppError extends Error {
  constructor(
    public statusCode: number,
    message: string,
  ) {
    super(message);
    this.name = "AppError";
  }
}
```

- Never swallow errors silently
- Log errors with context (request id, operation name)
- Centralise error handling in middleware, not in each route

## Async

- Always `await` or `return` promises — never fire-and-forget
- Use `Promise.all()` for independent async operations
- Never mix `async/await` with raw `.then()` chains

## Testing

- Unit test pure functions and services
- Integration test API routes
- Name tests: `should [behaviour] when [condition]`
- Arrange-Act-Assert structure
